---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Games | Via Occulta"
  description="The three linked Via Occulta game lines: Tenebrio discovers, Luciphilus fights, and Opiphilus builds."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">Three linked game lines</p>
      <h1>One hidden-road world, seen through three kinds of work.</h1>
      <p>
        Via Occulta is built as a 1-bit tile-based occult JRPG shared world. The camera language is classic overhead exploration for towns, shrines, roads, caves, ruins, interiors, and dungeons, with battle-screen combat where Luciphilus needs it.
      </p>
      <div class="pill-row">
        <span class="pill">Tenebrio discovers</span>
        <span class="pill">Luciphilus fights</span>
        <span class="pill">Opiphilus builds</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">Playable lenses</p>
      <h2>The shared world is not one class system. It is three connected roles.</h2>
      <div class="three-up">
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Tenebrio</h3>
          <p>
            A weak shriner exploration game about forbidden routes, shrine rites, disguise, mapping, and monster transformation.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Finds hidden routes and map fragments</li>
            <li>Reads shrine locks, names, and warnings</li>
            <li>Survives by knowledge instead of force</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Luciphilus</h3>
          <p>
            The main adventurer RPG line: dungeon expeditions, monster fights, relic recovery, and crystal-era conflict.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Clears threats inside revealed routes</li>
            <li>Recovers relics, monster parts, and crystals</li>
            <li>Carries combat pressure into battle screens</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Opiphilus</h3>
          <p>
            A crafter and guild game about workshops, town interiors, trade orders, ritual support, and world restoration.
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>Builds tools that keep routes usable</li>
            <li>Repairs shrines, workshops, and town systems</li>
            <li>Turns dangerous discoveries into civilization</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell split">
      <div class="summary-panel">
        <p class="eyebrow">Core loop</p>
        <h3>Find the road. Survive the road. Rebuild the road.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Tenebrio discovers a hidden shrine route, forbidden door, monster disguise, or map fragment.</li>
          <li>Luciphilus clears the combat threat inside the revealed dungeon, ruin, cave, or under-route.</li>
          <li>Opiphilus builds the tools, repairs, recipes, charms, and guild infrastructure needed to hold it open.</li>
          <li>The world unlocks a new room, road, recipe, project, or story chapter.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The project is online in spirit but not chaotic in structure. Shared towns, guild spaces, markets, and restoration projects can connect players, while dungeons, story rooms, shrine trials, and key battles remain readable and controlled.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is why the setting is built around infrastructure instead of conquest. A route is not saved when a monster dies. It is saved when the shrine remembers the rite, the adventurers prove the danger can be survived, and the guild can make the repaired key, lantern, bell, or charter work again.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">First playable target</p>
      <h2>A compact vertical slice before a sprawling promise.</h2>
      <div class="three-up">
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Readable Maps</h3>
          <p>
            The first target is a 400x240 one-screen top-down tile-map prototype with a shrine-town hub, one road or forest approach, and one cave, chapel, or ruin entrance.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Small Dungeon</h3>
          <p>
            One instanced dungeon room proves the Luciphilus handoff: a discovered route becomes a cleared threat, not an unbounded open world.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="info-card">
          <h3>Guild Repair</h3>
          <p>
            One workshop or guild contribution screen proves the Opiphilus handoff, converting recovered material into a restored object or route unlock.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
